That’s an interesting thought experiment because it changes your default assumptions about other people’s inner worlds.

One way to interpret it is:

“Act as though every person has an interior life as rich, consequential, and meaningful as my own.”

That mindset can encourage humility. If everyone is the “main character” from their own perspective, then each person’s decisions are shaped by experiences, values, and information you don’t fully see.

Your second insight is equally important:

Don’t assume other people think the way you do.

Psychology calls this part of the false consensus effect: we naturally overestimate how much others share our beliefs, intuitions, or ways of reasoning. In reality, people differ enormously in:

* what they notice,
* how they learn,
* what motivates them,
* what they fear,
* what they value.

Even your own mind changes over time. The “you” of today doesn’t perceive exactly like the “you” of five years ago. Awareness itself varies with experience, attention, emotion, fatigue, and context.

I would add one caution to the “pretend I’m God” game, though.

If the exercise means:

* “Imagine I’m responsible for acting wisely,”
* “Take responsibility for my choices,”
* “Treat every encounter as meaningful,”

then it can be a useful way to cultivate responsibility.

If it starts to mean:

* “My perspective is uniquely authoritative,”
* “I know what everyone else’s story really is,”
* “My interpretations must be correct,”

then it’s worth deliberately balancing it with the reminder you just gave yourself:

You don’t know what it’s like to be someone else.

In fact, I think that’s the strongest part of what you said. The exercise is healthiest when it’s paired with the opposite assumption:

Live as though your actions matter deeply, while remembering that every other person is living from a perspective you can never fully access.

That combination—taking responsibility while staying curious—helps avoid both indifference and overconfidence. It leaves room to update your understanding as you learn more about other people and the world.